  "prompt": "Why is there no copyright on reaction videos on YouTube? People are making money with it?",
  "response": "There are actually several factors related to copyright for reaction videos:\n\n1. Fair Use Doctrine\n- In many jurisdictions, reaction videos can be considered \"fair use\" if they provide commentary, criticism, or transform the original content\n- Reaction videos often add new creative value through personal commentary\n\n2. Transformative Content\n- If the reaction adds significant original content or critique, it may be protected under copyright law\n- Simply reacting is different from just re-uploading someone else's content\n\n3. Content ID and Copyright Claims\n- Many original content creators can monetize or block reaction videos through YouTube's Content ID system\n- Some creators choose to allow reaction videos for publicity or engagement\n\n4. Legal Agreements\n- Some content creators explicitly permit or even encourage reaction videos\n- Some collaborate with reaction video creators\n\n5. Monetization Rules\n- YouTube has specific guidelines about monetizing content that uses others' material\n- Creators must add significant original commentary to qualify for monetization\n\n6. Potential Disputes\n- Copyright for reaction videos is still a somewhat gray legal area\n- Some creators do file copyright strikes or takedown notices\n\nWhile reaction videos are common, they're not universally free from potential copyright challenges. The legality depends on specific circumstances and the extent of original commentary.",
